he appears critically unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 98% on 15L oxygen via non-rebreather mask, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is unconscious with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 8 (E2 V2 M4). His pupils are dilated but reactive. A bitter almond smell is noted on his breath. His venous blood appears bright red. Cardiac monitoring shows sinus tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activated charcoal","Methylene blue","Pralidoxime","Sodium bicarbonate","Hydroxocobalamin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of acute cyanide poisoning, including unconsciousness, cardiovascular instability, and the characteristic bitter almond smell. The bright red venous blood occurs because tissues are unable to extract oxygen due to inhibition of cellular respiration by cyanide. The industrial setting of electroplating is a common source of cyanide exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxocobalamin\u003C/strong\u003E (vitamin B12) is the antidote of choice for acute cyanide poisoning. It binds cyanide to form cyanocobalamin, which is then excreted in urine. It should be administered immediately when cyanide poisoning is suspected, as delays increase mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for oral ingestion of various toxins, but is not effective for inhalational cyanide exposure. Additionally, it would be dangerous to administer to an unconscious patient without airway protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the treatment of tricyclic antidepressant overdose and severe salicylate poisoning. It would not be effective against cyanide toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylene blue\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat methemoglobinemia. While methemoglobinemia can present with cyanosis, this patient\u0027s bright red venous blood and industrial exposure make cyanide poisoning more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPralidoxime\u003C/strong\u003E is an antidote for organophosphate poisoning, which typically presents with cholinergic symptoms (salivation, lacrimation, urination, defecation, gastrointestinal distress, and emesis) that are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bitter almond smell and bright red venous blood are characteristic findings in cyanide poisoning.","Immediate administration of hydroxocobalamin is the treatment of choice for suspected cyanide poisoning.","Industrial exposure to cyanide commonly occurs in electroplating, mining, and plastic manufacturing."],"references":["Hydroxocobalamin. Life in the Fast Lane [Internet]. Available at: litfl.com/hydroxocobalamin/","Cyanide poisoning. UpToDate [Internet]. Available at: uptodate.com/contents/cyanide-poisoning","Hydroxocobalamin - Medical Countermeasures Database. Chemical Hazards Emergency Medical Management (CHEMM) [Internet]. Available at: chemm.hhs.gov/countermeasure_hydroxocobalamin.htm."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60166"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18433"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60166"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T15:38:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T15:39:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11151"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74683"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency 